Labs with solution

1. Path traversal (directory traversal)

What it is (short): attackers manipulate file path input (e.g., file=../../etc/passwd) to read files outside the web root, exposing configs, secrets, or credentials. 


Typical PortSwigger lab objective: craft a request that changes a filename parameter to retrieve /etc/passwd or other protected files. Labs range from simple ../ cases to filters / canonicalization bypasses. 


How labs are solved (steps):

Identify an input that accepts a filename (query param, upload path, image loader).

Try ../ sequences (e.g., ../../../../etc/passwd) and URL-encoded variants (%2e%2e%2f).

If blocked, try unicode/encoding bypasses, absolute path tricks, or null byte/alternate encodings.

Capture the response — if you see file contents, record the PoC. 


PoC sketch: GET /view?file=../../../../etc/passwd → server returns passwd contents. Include exact request + redacted response in repo. (Short script: simple Python requests to submit crafted filename.) 
portswigger.net

Remediation (dev):

Canonicalize and normalise paths server-side and reject anything that escapes intended directories.

Map user-supplied “file IDs” to server paths (don’t accept raw filenames).

Run app with least privileges; keep sensitive files outside web root. 

Detection / testing tips: try path traversal payload lists (raw ../, encoded forms, double-encoded, alternative separators), and enumerate all inputs that reference files. Automate with a fuzzer for file path vectors. 


Impact: arbitrary file read → credentials, keys, source code leak; if write is possible, can lead to code execution or persistent backdoors.


TL;DR lab note : low complexity, high impact. Demonstrate read of /etc/passwd (or similar). Show request/response and recommended allowlist-based remediation.


2. Access control (broken access control / privilege escalation)

What it is: users can access resources or actions beyond their permission level (vertical/horizontal privilege escalation). These flaws let non-admins do admin actions or access other users’ data.

Typical PortSwigger lab objective: bypass method-based, parameter-based, or cookie-based checks to promote your user to admin or access the admin panel. 



How labs are solved (steps):

Map the app’s authorization model (roles, endpoints requiring admin).

Try switching HTTP methods (POST→GET), tampering role parameters, manipulating cookies/session tokens, or using IDOR-style changes to resource IDs.

Use Burp to replay and alter requests until you access protected functionality. 



PoC sketch: change role=user → role=admin in a cookie or request body; or send GET /admin/delete?user=carlos when only POST should work — if accepted, record the proof. Include before/after screenshots. 


Remediation (dev):

Enforce server-side authorization checks on every request (don’t rely on client or method).

Use role checks tied to session identity; avoid using client-controllable fields to decide privileges.

Test with automated authorization test suites and denial-by-default rules. 


Detection / testing tips: enumerate endpoints, try tampering with IDs & methods, test horizontal/vertical escalation, try forced browsing to hidden URLs. Include test cases for method-based and parameter-based control bypass. 


Impact: immediate data exposure, account takeover, ability to perform destructive admin actions; often a gateway to full compromise. 


TL;DR lab note: show privilege escalation (become admin) by tampering a cookie/param or method. Emphasize server-side enforcement in mitigation.

3. Authentication weaknesses

What it is: flaws in verifying identity — weak login flow, predictable reset tokens, missing rate limits, or broken MFA implementations. These can allow brute force, login bypass, or account takeover. 


Typical PortSwigger lab objective: exploit weak authentication to bypass login (SQLi on login, weak password reset, or brute force allowed). 


How labs are solved (steps):

Identify auth endpoints (login, reset, token generation).

Test for common issues: SQL injection in username/password fields, missing rate limits, enumable responses for username existence, or insecurely encoded tokens.

If SQLi present, craft payload to bypass login or extract credentials. 


PoC sketch: POST /login with username=administrator'-- to bypass authentication (example SQLi login bypass). Include exact request and explanation. 


Remediation (dev):

Use parameterised queries / prepared statements; enforce rate limiting and account lockout; implement proper MFA and secure reset token generation.

Use constant-time comparisons and avoid username enumeration. 

Detection / testing tips: test login for SQLi, check password reset flows for predictable tokens, try automated credential stuffing or Weak-password detection. 


Impact: account takeover, unauthorized access to sensitive functions or data, lateral movement. 


TL;DR lab note: show login bypass or account compromise; include mitigation steps (prepared statements, MFA, rate limits).

4. Server-side request forgery (SSRF)

What it is: the app is tricked into making HTTP requests to URLs controlled by the attacker or internal services (e.g., http://169.254.169.254 for cloud metadata). SSRF is now a top API risk. 



Typical PortSwigger lab objective: use a stock check or URL fetch feature to access internal addresses (localhost or internal 192.168.x.x) and accomplish a task like deleting a user. 



How labs are solved (steps):

Find an input that the server treats as a URL to fetch.

Replace the target with http://localhost:8080/admin or a cloud metadata endpoint.

If direct fetch blocked, try alternate IP encodings, redirect chains, or exploiting SSRF via XXE. 


PoC sketch: change stock check URL to http://127.0.0.1:8080/admin/delete?user=carlos and trigger the functionality; show server-side effect. Emphasize cloud metadata theft (if present) as high severity. 



Remediation (dev):

Block internal IP ranges for user-supplied URLs; implement strict allowlists for external domains; enforce hostname validation and DNS resolution checks.

Where possible, avoid fetching arbitrary user-supplied URLs. Use a proxy with filtering or a queue with manual verification. 


Detection / testing tips: scan internal ranges using SSRF, try metadata endpoints, test for redirect-based SSRF, and include OOB detection for blind SSRF. 



Impact: internal service access, credential theft (cloud metadata), server pivoting — can lead to full infrastructure compromise. 


TL;DR lab note: show SSRF to internal service or metadata endpoint; recommend allowlists and blocking internal ranges. 


#5. File upload vulnerabilities

What it is: insecure handling of uploaded files lets attackers upload web shells, scripts, or poison application logic — leading to RCE or persistent compromise. 


Typical PortSwigger lab objective: upload a crafted file (e.g., PHP web shell or disguised extension) and execute it to achieve RCE / command execution. 


How labs are solved (steps):

Find an upload feature (avatar, attachment).

Bypass client-side/type checks by modifying Content-Type, extension, or content (e.g., image.jpg containing <?php ... ?>).

Upload, then access the uploaded file to get code execution or read server response. 


PoC sketch: upload shell.php renamed shell.php.jpg and try to access /uploads/shell.php.jpg (if the server executes based on content type or filename). Minimal PoC scripts can craft multipart uploads. 


Remediation (dev):

Validate file types server-side using magic bytes, store uploads outside the web root, rename files, and forbid execution permissions on upload folders.

Use content scanning, size limits, and strong allowlists (instead of blacklists). 


Detection / testing tips: test by uploading different extensions, change headers, attempt to upload polyglot files, and try direct access to stored files. 


Impact: remote code execution, persistent backdoors, data exfiltration. High severity when upload allows execution. 


TL;DR lab note: show an upload → execute flow (or upload that reveals server info). Emphasize storing uploads outside webroot and strict server-side validation. 


6. OS command injection (shell injection)

What it is: user input is passed to OS command execution without neutralization, allowing arbitrary commands to run on server. Full server compromise is common. 


Typical PortSwigger lab objective: inject ; whoami or chaining operators into an OS-invoking parameter (stock checker, ping function) to get command output or cause side effects. 


How labs are solved (steps):

Find an app function that runs OS commands with user input (e.g., ping, traceroute, stock check).

Inject command separators (;, &&) or use blind techniques (time delays) for blind injection.

Capture output or measure timing for blind scenarios. 


PoC sketch: GET /stock?product=1;whoami and show response contains www-data or other user; for blind: inject ; sleep 10 and observe delayed response. 



Remediation (dev):

Avoid shelling out with user input. If needed, use safe APIs that separate arguments (no shell interpolation), validate/allowlist inputs, and drop privileges.

Use least-privilege service accounts and disable unnecessary shell access. 


Detection / testing tips: test with typical separators and timing attacks; use OOB when output isn’t returned. 


Impact: complete server compromise, data theft, pivoting to internal systems. 


TL;DR lab note: demonstrate whoami or sleep technique; recommend safe APIs and argument isolation. 


7. SQL Injection (SQLi)

What it is: attacker injects SQL into queries built from user input, enabling data extraction, modification, or DB operations. Classic and high-impact. 



Typical PortSwigger lab objective: exploit SQLi to bypass login, extract hidden data, or list DB contents via error or blind techniques. Labs include login bypass, retrieve hidden rows, blind boolean/conditional, and time-based. 



How labs are solved (steps):

Identify input used in SQL queries (filters, login fields).

Test with ' OR '1'='1 style payloads, comment out rest of query ('--) or use union/stacked queries depending on DB.

For blind SQLi, use boolean/time-based payloads to extract data bit-by-bit. 



PoC sketch: login bypass: username=administrator'-- in a login POST to get in as admin; or boolean blind to extract characters using SUBSTRING and conditional responses. 


Remediation (dev):

Use parameterised queries / prepared statements, ORMs properly, and strong input validation/escaping. Limit DB privileges and use WAFs for extra protection. 


Detection / testing tips: test all inputs, use automated scanners, try both error-based and blind approaches; check DB errors in responses and time-based anomalies. 


Impact: data theft, data manipulation, potential RCE via DB functions — critical severity. 


TL;DR lab note: show login bypass or data retrieval. Emphasize prepared statements and least-privilege DB roles. 


8. Insecure Deserialization

What it is: the application deserializes attacker-controlled data into objects and executes code paths (or dangerous methods) leading to RCE, state changes, or privilege escalation. 


Typical PortSwigger lab objective: edit serialized object in cookie/session to trigger an operation (delete file or escalate privileges). Labs show using built-in gadget chains or application functions to exploit. 



How labs are solved (steps):

Identify serialized blobs (cookies, session tokens).

Modify object fields (e.g., set isAdmin=true) or inject payloads that cause the app to call a dangerous method.

If languages support gadget chains (Java/PHP/Ruby), use tools to craft payloads. 


PoC sketch: modify serialized session cookie to set user.role=admin and show admin-only page accessible; or craft a payload that calls File.delete() to remove a file. Include exact cookie value changes and before/after. 


Remediation (dev):

Avoid deserializing untrusted data. Use safe formats (JSON) and explicit parsing, versioned schemas, or allowlists; use deserialization libraries without remote gadget chains. Validate objects after deserialization. 


Detection / testing tips: look for serialized cookies, test tampering of object fields, and try common gadget chains with existing tools. 


Impact: RCE, privilege escalation, data corruption — very high severity when exploitable. 


TL;DR lab note: edit serialized session to perform action (delete file / become admin). Recommend disallowing untrusted deserialization and using safer formats.